SAN FRANCISCO – Embattled tech giant Hewlett-Packard said Wednesday it would slash 27,000 jobs, 8% of its worldwide workforce, by 2014 in hopes of saving billions of dollars and reversing a financial funk amid brutal competition.

The multiyear restructuring plan, which aims to save $3 billion to $3.5 billion, is the biggest in HP's 73-year history and "absolutely critical for the long-term success of the company," CEO Meg Whitman said in a conference call. "
